    <section id="sect-00001">
    <title>Oxidation of Alkyl Side Chains</title>
    <para id="para-00001">Despite its unsaturation, the benzene ring is inert to strong oxidizing agents such as KMnO<sub>4</sub>, which will cleave alkene carbon–carbon bonds <emphasis effect="bold">(<link document="m00096">Section 8.8</link>)</emphasis>. It turns out, however, that the presence of the aromatic ring has a dramatic effect on the reactivity of alkyl side chains. These side chains react rapidly with oxidizing agents and are converted into carboxyl groups,  – CO<sub>2</sub>H.The net effect is conversion of an alkylbenzene into a benzoic acid, <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>Ar</m:mtext><m:mo>–</m:mo><m:mtext>R</m:mtext><m:mo>→</m:mo><m:mtext>Ar</m:mtext><m:mo>–</m:mo><m:msub><m:mrow><m:mtext>CO</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mtext>H</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math>. Butylbenzene is oxidized by aqueous KMnO<sub>4</sub> to give benzoic acid, for instance.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which butylbenzene reacts in the presence of pink KMnO4 and water to yield Benzoic acid (85%). Butylbenzene shows a benzene with C1 bonded to a butyl group. Benzoic acid shows a benzene with C1 bonded to a carboxyl group. The oxygen atom and hydroxyl group are shown in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_16_08_001.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00002">A similar oxidation is employed industrially for the preparation of the terephthalic acid used in the production of polyester fibers. Worldwide, approximately 118 million tons per year of terephthalic acid is produced by oxidation of <emphasis effect="italics">p</emphasis>-xylene, using air as the oxidant and Co(III) salts as catalyst.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which p-xylene reacts in the presence of pink oxygen and Co (III) to yield Terephthalic acid. p-Xylene shows a benzene with C1 and C4 bonded to a methyl group each. Terephthalic acid shows a benzene with C1 and C4 bonded to a carboxyl group each. The oxygen atoms and hydroxyl groups are shown in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_16_08_002.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00003">The mechanism of side-chain oxidation is complex and involves reaction of C – H bonds at the position next to the aromatic ring to form intermediate benzylic radicals. <emphasis effect="italics">tert</emphasis>-Butylbenzene has no benzylic hydrogens, however, and is therefore inert.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which tert-Butylbenzene reacts in the presence of pink KMnO4 and water. Text reads: No reaction. tert-Butylbenzene shows a benzene bonded to a carbon that is bonded to three methyl groups.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_16_08_003.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00004">Analogous side-chain oxidations occur in various biosynthetic pathways. The neurotransmitter norepinephrine, for instance, is biosynthesized from dopamine by a benzylic hydroxylation reaction. The process is catalyzed by the copper-containing enzyme dopamine <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-monooxygenase and occurs by a radical mechanism. A copper–oxygen species in the enzyme first abstracts the <emphasis effect="italics">pro-</emphasis>R benzylic hydrogen to give a radical, and a hydroxyl is then transferred from copper to carbon.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which Dopamine yields an intermediate that further yields Norepinephrine. Dopamine shows benzene bonded to two hydroxyl groups and a 2-carbon chain. C1 of the chain is dash bonded to a hydrogen wedge bonded to a pink hydrogen. C2 is bonded to an amino group. The intermediate shows benzene bonded to two hydroxyl groups and a 2-carbon chain. C1 of the chain is bonded to a hydrogen and shows an electron. C2 is bonded to an amino group. Norepinephrine is similar to dopamine but the pink hydrogen is replaced by a pink hydroxyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_16_08_004.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
