    <section id="sect-00003">
    <title>Bromination of Alkylbenzene Side Chains</title>
    <para id="para-00006">Side-chain bromination at the benzylic position occurs when an alkylbenzene is treated with <emphasis effect="italics">N</emphasis>-bromosuccinimide (NBS). For example, propylbenzene gives (1-bromopropyl)benzene in 97% yield on reaction with NBS in the presence of benzoyl peroxide, (PhCO<sub>2</sub>)<sub>2</sub>, as a radical initiator. Bromination occurs exclusively in the benzylic position next to the aromatic ring and does not give a mixture of products.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which propylbenzene reacts in the presence of N-bromosuccinimide (PhCO2)2 and CCl4 to yield (1-Bromopropyl)benzene (97%) and succinimide (shown in parentheses). Propylbenzene shows a benzene bonded to a propyl group. N-bromosuccinimide shows a 5-membered ring with a nitrogen bonded to a pink bromine. The ring is double bonded to two oxygen atoms.(1-Bromopropyl)benzene shows a benzene bonded to a methine group that is bonded to a pink bromine and ethyl group. The other product is similar to N-bromosuccinimide but the bromine is replaced by a hydrogen.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_16_08_006.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00007">The mechanism of benzylic bromination is similar to that discussed in <emphasis effect="bold"><link document="m00115">Section 10.3</link></emphasis> for allylic bromination of alkenes. Abstraction of a benzylic hydrogen atom first generates an intermediate benzylic radical, which then reacts with Br<sub>2</sub> in step 2 to yield product and a <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>Br</m:mtext><m:mo>·</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> radical, which cycles back into the reaction to carry on the chain. The Br<sub>2</sub> needed for reaction with the benzylic radical is produced in step 3 by a concurrent reaction of HBr with NBS.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00006">
    <media alt="An illustration shows three steps of a reaction. In the first step a reactant reacts with pink bromine radical to yield an intermediate benzylic radical and HBr in which H is green and Br is pink. In step 2 the benzylic radical reacts with Br2 to yield product and a bromine radical which cycles back into the step 1 of the reaction. In step 3 HBr reacts with NBS to yield pink bromine and another product. The first reactant shows a benzene bonded to a carbon bonded to R hydrogen and a green hydrogen. The benzylic radical shows a benzene bonded to a carbon bonded to R and hydrogen. The carbon shows an electron. The product of step 2 shows a benzene bonded to a carbon bonded to R pink Br and hydrogen. NBS shows a 5-membered ring with a nitrogen bonded to pink bromine. The ring is double bonded to two oxygen atoms. The product of step 3 shows a 5-membered ring with a nitrogen bonded to green hydrogen. The ring is double bonded to two oxygen atoms.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_16_08_007.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00008">Reaction occurs exclusively at the benzylic position because the benzylic radical intermediate is stabilized by resonance. <link target-id="fig-00007"/> shows how the benzyl radical is stabilized by overlap of its <emphasis effect="italics">p</emphasis> orbital with the ringed <emphasis effect="italics">π</emphasis> electron system.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00007">
    <media alt="An illustration shows four resonance forms of benzyl radicals and an electrostatic potential map. The first form shows a benzene bonded to a carbon that shows an electron and is bonded to two hydrogens. An arrow from the electron points to the bond between the ring and the carbon. Two arrows from a double bond of benzene point outward. The second form shows a cyclohexane with two double bonds double bonded to a methylene group. A carbon of the ring shows an electron. An arrow from the electron points to the adjacent C-C bond. Two arrows from a double bond of benzene point outward. The third form is similar to the third form but another carbon shows an electron and the arrows point from another double bond. The fourth form shows a cyclohexane with two double bonds double bonded to a methylene group. A carbon shows an electron. The electrostatic potential map shows the fourth form with gray balls (carbons) and white balls (hydrogens).Three arrows point to three carbon atoms of the ring. The region around the other carbons is shown in red surrounded by yellow. An arrow points to the carbon of methylene group and the region surrounded by this carbon is purple.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_16_08_008.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption>A resonance-stabilized benzylic radical. The spin-density surface shows that the <emphasis effect="bold"><span class="cyan-text">unpaired electron</span></emphasis> is shared by the ortho and para carbons of the ring.</caption>
    </figure>
    </section>
